                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>A widow! what a world of sorrow<lb/> and care is comprised in that epithet,<lb/> if\n                young, he of whom she is bereaved<lb/> was yet the object of those warm and<lb/>\n                gushing affections whose light was the<lb/> bright dream of her maidenhood, and<lb/>\n                if of maturer age, years of companionship<lb/> had <add>?</add> those ardent\n                feelings only to<lb/> purify <del>them</del> them; the hours of calm<lb/> converse,\n                the plans <del>the</del> hopes, wishes of<lb/><sic>of</sic> which their children\n                were the theme,<lb/> all have served to deepen the love<lb/> that in the early\n                season of their wedded<lb/> life seemed incapable of greater intensity;<lb/> and now\n                at none she weeps alone, in<lb/> the first anguish of bereavement what can<lb/>\n                console her. Has she ceased to love her<lb/> children, no no but in looking on\n                them<lb/> she only thinks alas he is no longer here<lb/> to watch with me their\n                growing loveli-<lb/>ness, to check their wayward deed or<lb/> train to better\n                thought. But now there<lb/> comes a holy calm, whence is it? see</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3gt5fz0f/canvas/p1"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
